+# Getting Sen STL recognised by GitHub Linguist
+
+Once Linguist knows about Sen STL, GitHub will syntax-highlight `.stl` files
+when people browse the Sen repository (and any other repo containing them)
+on github.com. It also makes STL show up in per-repo language statistics.
+
+The process has two sides:
+
+1. **Publish the TextMate grammar to a standalone public GitHub repo** so
+   Linguist can reference it as a git submodule.
+2. **Open a PR against `github-linguist/linguist`** with four edits:
+   `languages.yml`, `grammars.yml`, `heuristics.yml`, and `samples/Sen STL/`.
+
+## Pre-flight: .stl conflicts with stereolithography
+
+The extension `.stl` is already registered in Linguist for
+stereolithography (3D-printing) files. Without a disambiguation
+heuristic, Linguist maintainers will (rightly) reject the PR.
+
+The `heuristics-entry.yml` file in this directory provides a heuristic
+that distinguishes the two based on file content:
+- **Sen STL** files have a `package ...;` declaration or an STL keyword
+  (`class`, `struct`, `enum`, `variant`, `interface`, `sequence`,
+  `array`, `optional`, `quantity`, `alias`) near the top.
+- **Stereolithography ASCII** starts with `solid <name>` on line 1.
+
+## Step-by-step
+
+### 1. Publish the grammar
+
+Create a new public repo, for example `https://github.com/<org>/sen-stl-textmate`,
+whose contents mirror the
+`resources/syntax_highlighting/stl/vscode/` directory of the Sen repo. The
+minimum required layout is:
+
+```
+sen-stl-textmate/
+├── LICENSE
+├── README.md
+├── package.json
+└── syntaxes/
+    └── stl.tmLanguage.json
+```
+
+Tag a release (e.g. `v0.1.0`) so Linguist's submodule has a stable commit
+to pin.
+
+> Why a separate repo? Linguist vendors every grammar as a git submodule
+> under `vendor/grammars/`. Pointing at a separate repo is the normal
+> pattern and keeps Linguist from pulling the entire Sen tree.
+
+### 2. Fork `github-linguist/linguist` and make four edits
+
+Clone your Linguist fork, then:
+
+#### 2a. `lib/linguist/languages.yml`
+
+Add the entry from [`languages-entry.yml`](languages-entry.yml) alphabetically.
+Leave `language_id` as the placeholder; a Linguist maintainer will assign a
+real number during review.
+
+#### 2b. `vendor/grammars.yml` and the submodule
+
+Add the submodule and the entry from [`grammars-entry.yml`](grammars-entry.yml):
+
+```bash
+git submodule add https://github.com/<org>/sen-stl-textmate \
+                  vendor/grammars/sen-stl-textmate
+# then paste the grammars-entry.yml snippet into vendor/grammars.yml,
+# keeping the file sorted.
+```
+
+#### 2c. `lib/linguist/heuristics.yml`
+
+Extend the existing `.stl` disambiguation block with the rules from
+[`heuristics-entry.yml`](heuristics-entry.yml). Do **not** add a second
+`- extensions: ['.stl']` block - merge into the existing one.
+
+#### 2d. `samples/Sen STL/`
+
+Copy 3-5 representative `.stl` files from the Sen repo. See
+[`sample-selection.md`](sample-selection.md) for guidance.
+
+### 3. Verify locally
+
+```bash
+bundle install
+bundle exec rake samples   # rebuild the classifier index
+bundle exec rake test      # run Linguist's test suite
+```
+
+All tests should pass, and `script/licensed` (if prompted) should accept
+the new submodule's LICENSE (Apache-2.0 in our case).
+
+### 4. Open the PR
+
+Commit each change logically (one commit per file is fine) and open the PR
+against `github-linguist/linguist:main`. Include in the PR body:
+
+- A short description of Sen STL (a few sentences) plus a link to
+  [`docs/users_guide/stl.md`](../../../../docs/users_guide/stl.md) or
+  [`docs/users_guide/stl_grammar.md`](../../../../docs/users_guide/stl_grammar.md).
+- A link to the standalone grammar repo.
+- A note that the PR resolves the `.stl` / stereolithography conflict with a
+  heuristic, and that all five samples classify correctly.
+
+## Keeping the grammar in sync
+
+When the Sen-side grammar changes under `resources/syntax_highlighting/stl/vscode/`:
+
+1. Mirror the diff to the standalone grammar repo and tag a release.
+2. In a new PR against Linguist, bump the submodule pointer to the new tag.
+3. Re-run `bundle exec rake test`.
+
+No Linguist PR is needed for grammar fixes that don't change the language's
+public surface (keywords, operators, file extension).
